<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,1147]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,318,422,448]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Body" baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[325,541,422,448]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvibarbis">Efferia fulvibarbis</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by it large, robust body [
<quantity box="[1027,1161,422,448]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="2.9" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="23.0" valueMax="29.0" valueMin="17.0">17–29 mm</quantity>
], reddish face and legs; femora mostly blackish-red, sometimes black ventrally, apices red; mostly yellowish or reddish vestiture, vein R5 curved forward meeting costa before wing apex, and in the combined characters of the terminalia (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 33–38" captionStartId="23.[151,269,1930,1954]" captionTargetBox="[198,1401,431,1913]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[195,1401,358,1913]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 33–38. Efferia fulvibarbis (Macquart). Male terminalia, lateral view: 33. Intact, left side; 34. Gonostylus with thick sclerotization; 35. Phallus; and 36. Aedeagus with tubes and phallic flange. Female terminalia, lateral view: 37. Ovipositor; 38. Median and lateral spermatheca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455824/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Figs. 33–38</figureCitation>
). The male is further recognized by the strongly dilated wing and the female by the long narrow ovipositor.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,1147]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Macquart’s specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Body" baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[504,665,619,644]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvibarbis">
<emphasis box="[504,665,619,644]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. fulvibarbis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are presumed lost (
<bibRefCitation box="[901,1212,618,644]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="ref39115" refString="Martin, C H. &amp; Papavero, N. (1970) A catalogue of the Diptera of the Americas south of the United States. Bulletin 35 b. Family Asildae. Museu de Zoologia, Universidade de Sao Paulo, 139 pp., Sao Paulo." type="book">Martin &amp; Papavero, 1970</bibRefCitation>
). However, we are convinced that it and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Martin &amp; Papavero" authorityYear="1970" box="[427,622,657,682]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pachychaeta">
<emphasis box="[427,622,657,682]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. pachychaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[641,881,657,683]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<collectionCode box="[641,714,657,683]" country="Australia" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/93c9-w2q7" name="University of Newcastle" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">NEW</collectionCode>
<collectionCode box="[723,881,657,683]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">SYNONYM</collectionCode>
</emphasis>
) are the same species based on the original description, size and color of the body, and 
<typeStatus box="[673,724,696,722]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">type</typeStatus>
locality. Both are the larger species in Hispaniola and were originally reported from the vicinity of Bois Caradeux - Port-au-Prince in eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1154,1219,735,761]" name="Haiti" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Haiti</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation box="[1231,1436,735,761]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" refId="ref39224" refString="Macquart, J. M. P. (1848) Dipteres exotiques nouveaux ou peu connus. Suite du 2 me supplement [i. e., 3 e supplement]. Memoires de la Societe Royale des Sciences de l`Agriculture et des Arts, Lille 1847 (2), 161 - 237, 7 pls. (Also separately published, pp. 1 - 77, 7 pls., Paris, 1848)." type="book chapter">Macquart (1848)</bibRefCitation>
states that the thorax is red [‘thorace rufo’]. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Body" baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[679,898,774,799]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvibarbis">
<emphasis box="[679,898,774,799]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Efferia fulvibarbis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species that has a reddish body, a moderately or strongly dilated wing, and the sides of the abdominal tergites are yellowish-gray tomentose. Additionally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Perez-Gelabert" authorityYear="2009" box="[318,432,851,876]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exacta">
<emphasis box="[318,432,851,876]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. exacta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, another large species that is frequently misidentified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Body" baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[1128,1294,851,876]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvibarbis">
<emphasis box="[1128,1294,851,876]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. fulvibarbis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in museum collections, is black with abundant black bristles on the head thorax, coxae, and legs; the costal margin is straight, not dilated; and the pleura and sides of the tergites are dark yellowish-brown or reddish-brown tomentose. Furthermore, the apical corners of tergites 2–4 have large, white, tomentose spots, often triangular in shape.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,1147]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Two forms of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Body" baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[372,596,1044,1070]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Efferia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvibarbis">Efferia fulvibarbis</taxonomicName>
exist. Older museum specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[1070,1131,1044,1070]" name="Haiti" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Haiti</collectingCountry>
are mostly red and large (
<quantity box="[159,291,1082,1108]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="2.9" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="25.0" valueMax="29.0" valueMin="21.0">21–29 mm</quantity>
) whereas newer material from 
<collectingCountry box="[662,837,1082,1108]" name="Dominican Republic" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">the Dominican</collectingCountry>
Republic is more nearly black with partly reddish femora and have a wider range in size (
